VALUES
(40, 21, 31, 54, 1, 13, 16, 'the publicans and the harlots', 'Mercy and Acceptance of Sinners', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s mercy towards those considered sinners. Both passages emphasize that those who seem farthest from righteousness, like publicans and harlots, can receive grace and enter the kingdom of God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 32, 42, 7, 37, 50, 'believed him not', 'Faith and Forgiveness Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of belief and forgiveness. In Matthew, the publicans and harlots believed John, while in Luke, the sinful woman demonstrates her faith through acts of love and receives forgiveness. This connection highlights the contrast between those who repent and believe versus those who do not.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 32, 38, 7, 11, 12, 'ye believed him not', 'Rejection of Prophetic Messages', 'This connection highlights the theme of refusal to listen to God''s messengers. Both passages emphasize the stubbornness of the people in rejecting the words of the prophets, leading to consequences.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 32, 40, 21, 25, 25, 'believed him not', 'Connection of Belief in John', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of belief in John the Baptist. In Matthew 21:25, the question of John''s authority highlights the failure to believe, which is echoed in Matthew 21:32 where the publicans and harlots believed him while others did not.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 32, 42, 7, 29, 30, 'believed him not', 'Response to John''s Ministry', 'This connection highlights the contrasting responses to John the Baptist''s ministry. Both passages emphasize the belief of publicans and the rejection by the Pharisees, illustrating differing attitudes toward repentance and righteousness.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 32, 61, 2, 21, 21, 'the way of righteousness', 'Connection of Righteousness and Rejection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''the way of righteousness'' and the consequences of rejecting it. Matthew highlights the failure to believe John, while 2 Peter warns against turning away after knowing the truth.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 32, 19, 81, 11, 12, 'believed him not', 'Rejection of God''s Message', 'Both passages emphasize the refusal to heed God''s call. In Matthew, the people did not believe John, while in Psalms, Israel would not listen to God''s voice.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 32, 23, 35, 8, 8, 'the way of righteousness', 'Connection of Righteousness and Belief', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief in righteousness. Both passages emphasize the importance of following the right path, with Matthew referencing those who believed John and Isaiah describing a way of holiness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 33, 23, 5, 1, 4, NULL, 'Vineyard Imagery Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the imagery of a vineyard, including elements like a tower and a winepress. This connection highlights the themes of care and expectation in the cultivation of the vineyard.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 33, 41, 12, 1, 12, 'planted a vineyard', 'Vineyard Parable Connection', 'Both passages emphasize a vineyard planted by a householder, illustrating the relationship between the owner and the husbandmen. The narrative in Mark expands on the consequences of the husband''s actions, highlighting the rejection of the owner''s son.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 33, 42, 20, 9, 19, 'planted a vineyard', 'Parable of the Vineyard', 'Both passages emphasize a vineyard planted by a householder or man, illustrating the relationship between the owner and the husbandmen. The narrative in both accounts highlights the rejection of the owner''s servants and ultimately his son, symbolizing a deeper message about authority and accountability.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 33, 24, 2, 21, 21, 'planted a vineyard', 'Vineyard Imagery Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a vineyard, representing God''s people. Matthew describes a householder who plants a vineyard, while Jeremiah speaks of God planting a noble vine, highlighting the relationship between God and His people.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 33, 22, 8, 11, 12, 'let it out to husbandmen', 'Vineyard Ownership and Stewardship', 'This connection highlights the theme of vineyard ownership and stewardship in both passages. The householder in Matthew and Solomon in Song of Solomon both entrust their vineyards to keepers, emphasizing the responsibility of caretaking for what belongs to them.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 33, 19, 80, 8, 16, 'planted a vineyard', 'Vineyard Imagery Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a vineyard, representing God''s care and cultivation. Matthew''s parable of the vineyard owner parallels the imagery in Psalms of God planting and nurturing a vine, highlighting themes of stewardship and divine expectation.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 33, 39, 2, 4, 9, NULL, 'Covenant and Stewardship Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the responsibility of caretakers in a covenant relationship. The householder in Matthew entrusts the vineyard to husbandmen, paralleling the covenant with Levi in Malachi, where priests are expected to uphold the law and guide the people.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 34, 42, 20, 10, 19, 'the fruits of it', 'Parable of the Vineyard', 'Both passages emphasize the sending of servants to the husbandmen, illustrating the rejection of those sent to collect the fruits. This connection highlights the theme of accountability and the consequences of rejecting the owner''s authority.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 34, 23, 5, 4, 4, 'the fruits of it', 'Vineyard and Fruit Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the expectation of fruit from a vineyard. In Matthew, the servants are sent to receive the fruits, while Isaiah questions why the vineyard produced wild grapes instead of expected fruit.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 34, 38, 1, 3, 6, 'receive the fruits of it', 'Call to Repentance and Response', 'Both passages emphasize the sending of servants to call for a response. In Matthew, the servants seek the fruits, while Zechariah urges a turning back to God, highlighting the expectation of a fruitful response.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 34, 12, 17, 13, 23, 'sent his servants to the husbandmen', 'God''s Call for Accountability', 'Both passages emphasize the sending of servants to receive fruits or testimonies from the people. In Matthew, the servants are sent to collect fruits, while in 2 Kings, the Lord sends prophets to call Israel and Judah to repentance. This connection highlights the theme of divine expectation and accountability.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 34, 14, 36, 15, 16, 'sent his servants to the husbandmen', 'Connection of God''s Messengers', 'Both passages emphasize the sending of messengers to receive what is due. In Matthew, the servants are sent to collect fruits, while in 2 Chronicles, God sends messengers to His people. This connection highlights the theme of divine communication and the response of the people.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 34, 16, 9, 29, 30, 'sent his servants to the husbandmen', 'Divine Forbearance and Rejection', 'This connection highlights the theme of God sending messengers to receive a response from His people. Both passages emphasize the rejection of God''s servants and the consequences of not heeding His call.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 34, 22, 8, 11, 12, 'fruits of it', 'Vineyard and Fruit Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a vineyard and the expectation of fruit. In Matthew, the servants are sent to receive the fruits, while in Song of Solomon, the keepers are responsible for bringing the fruit, highlighting a shared theme of stewardship and accountability.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 35, 14, 36, 15, 16, 'beat one, and killed another', 'Rejection of God''s Messengers', 'Both passages emphasize the mistreatment of God''s messengers. In Matthew, the husbandmen beat and killed servants, paralleling the mocking and misuse of prophets in 2 Chronicles.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 35, 16, 9, 26, 26, NULL, 'Rejection of Prophets', 'Both passages emphasize the violent rejection of God''s messengers. In Matthew, the husbandmen kill and beat servants, while in Nehemiah, the people slay prophets who testify against them.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 35, 40, 5, 12, 12, 'killed another', 'Persecution of Prophets Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the persecution of God''s messengers. In Matthew 21:35, the servants are mistreated, paralleling the persecution of prophets mentioned in Matthew 5:12.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 35, 58, 11, 36, 37, 'stoned', 'Persecution of God''s Servants', 'Both passages emphasize the suffering and violence faced by God''s messengers. Matthew describes the brutal treatment of the servants, while Hebrews lists various forms of persecution, including being stoned.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 35, 44, 7, 52, 52, 'killed another', 'Persecution of Servants and Prophets', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of persecution against God''s messengers. In Matthew, the husbandmen beat and killed the servants, while in Acts, the fathers are accused of slaying the prophets who foretold the coming of the Just One.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 35, 40, 23, 31, 37, NULL, 'Connection of Prophetic Violence', 'Both passages emphasize the violent treatment of prophets. In Matthew 21:35, the servants are beaten and killed, paralleling Matthew 23:31-37, where Jesus condemns the killing of prophets by the current generation. This connection highlights the ongoing cycle of violence against those sent by God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 35, 42, 13, 33, 34, 'killed another, and stoned another', 'Connection of Prophetic Rejection', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection and violence against God''s messengers. In Matthew, the husbandmen kill and stone the servants, while in Luke, Jerusalem is described as killing and stoning the prophets sent to them.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 36, 40, 22, 4, 4, 'sent other servants', 'Sending of Servants', 'Both passages emphasize the act of sending servants. In Matthew 21:36, the servants are mistreated, while in Matthew 22:4, new servants are sent to invite guests to a feast.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
